    "accordion_wWymTR": {
      "type": "accordion",
      "blocks": {
        "accor_item_pbDaxQ": {
          "type": "accor_item",
          "settings": {
            "icon": "none",
            "title": "What are open-ear headphones?",
            "content": "<p>Open-ear headphones, also known as <strong>outside ear headphones</strong>, are innovative audio devices that allow you to listen to music or take calls without covering or inserting anything into your ears. They leave your ear canals open, providing a safer and more comfortable listening experience, especially for outdoor activities. Unlike traditional headphones, open-ear headphones let you stay aware of your surroundings, making them ideal for running, cycling, and commuting.</p>"
          }
        },
        "accor_item_Eejd9D": {
          "type": "accor_item",
          "settings": {
            "icon": "none",
            "title": "What does open-ear headphones mean?",
            "content": "<p>The term open-ear headphones (sometimes referred to as <strong>out ear headphones</strong>) refers to headphones designed to sit outside your ears rather than inside or over them. Using technologies like air conduction or bone conduction, these headphones deliver sound while keeping your ears open. This design promotes safety and comfort, particularly for those who value situational awareness and ear safety.</p>"
          }
        },
        "accor_item_n8YwXt": {
          "type": "accor_item",
          "settings": {
            "icon": "none",
            "title": "How do open-ear headphones work?",
            "content": "<p>Open-ear headphones, including <strong>outside ear headphones</strong>, use either air conduction or bone conduction technology to transmit sound. Air conduction headphones direct sound waves toward your ear without sealing the ear canal. Bone conduction headphones, on the other hand, send vibrations through your cheekbones directly to your inner ear, bypassing the eardrum. This allows you to enjoy high-quality audio while staying connected to your environment.</p>"
          }
        },
        "accor_item_8Q638E": {
          "type": "accor_item",
          "settings": {
            "icon": "none",
            "title": "How do bone conduction open-ear headphones work?",
            "content": "<p>Bone conduction headphones work by transmitting sound through vibrations on your cheekbones, bypassing the eardrum entirely. The vibrations travel directly to the cochlea in your inner ear, where they are processed as sound. This technology is particularly beneficial for people with certain types of hearing loss and for those who want to protect their eardrums while enjoying music and office calls, etc.</p>"
          }
        },
        "accor_item_AzxY7F": {
          "type": "accor_item",
          "settings": {
            "icon": "none",
            "title": "Why are open-ear headphones better?",
            "content": "<p>Open-ear headphones, or out ear headphones, are better because they prioritize your safety and comfort. Unlike traditional earbuds or over-ear headphones, they don’t block your ears, allowing you to stay aware of your surroundings. Whether you are jogging in traffic or working in a busy office, open-ear headphones provide an excellent balance between audio quality and environmental awareness.</p>"
          }
        },
        "accor_item_CbHbwG": {
          "type": "accor_item",
          "settings": {
            "icon": "none",
            "title": "What are the benefits of open-ear headphones?",
            "content": "<ul><li><strong>Safety:</strong> Stay aware of your surroundings, especially in outdoor or busy environments.</li><li><strong>Comfort:</strong> No pressure at all on your ears, reducing ear fatigue.</li><li><strong>Health:</strong> Avoid the risks of ear infections or pain from prolonged use of traditional earbuds.</li><li><strong>Versatility:</strong> Ideal for workouts, commuting, office calls, and casual listening.</li></ul>"
          }
        },
        "accor_item_BxnijW": {
          "type": "accor_item",
          "settings": {
            "icon": "none",
            "title": "Are open-ear headphones good for ear health?",
            "content": "<p>Yes, open-ear headphones, including <strong>outside ear headphones</strong>, are great for ear health. Not blocking the ear canal, they reduce the risk of earwax buildup, infections, and discomfort. Bone conduction headphones bypass the eardrum entirely, protecting your hearing over time while still delivering clear and immersive audio.</p>"
          }
        },
        "accor_item_XQG8tG": {
          "type": "accor_item",
          "settings": {
            "icon": "none",
            "title": "Can you wear open-ear headphones with glasses?",
            "content": "<p>Absolutely! Open-ear headphones are designed to sit comfortably around your ears, making them compatible with any type of glasses. Their lightweight and ergonomic design ensures that they don’t interfere with your eyewear, whether you are using them for work, sports, or regular activities.</p>"
          }
        },
        "accor_item_CY4LEE": {
          "type": "accor_item",
          "settings": {
            "icon": "none",
            "title": "Can other people hear open-ear headphones?",
            "content": "<p>Open-ear headphones, or <strong>out ear headphones</strong>, are designed to minimize sound leakage. While air conduction headphones might emit faint sounds at high volumes, bone conduction headphones are almost silent to others. This makes them a discreet choice for calls and music in shared spaces.</p>"
          }
        },
        "accor_item_dD9GEc": {
          "type": "accor_item",
          "settings": {
            "icon": "none",
            "title": "Do open-ear headphones sound better?",
            "content": "<p>Open-ear headphones deliver excellent sound quality while allowing ambient noise to pass through. Although they may not offer the same noise isolation as traditional earbuds, they provide a more natural listening experience. Bone conduction headphones, in particular, excel in environments where situational awareness is key.</p>"
          }
        },
        "accor_item_GNJyky": {
          "type": "accor_item",
          "settings": {
            "icon": "none",
            "title": "What are the use cases of open-ear headphones?",
            "content": "<ul><li>Outdoor activities like running, cycling, and hiking.</li><li>Commuting while staying alert to traffic and announcements.</li><li>Office environments where you need to remain aware of colleagues.</li><li>Listening to music or podcasts during casual walks or workouts.</li></ul>"
          }
        },
        "accor_item_WUnNri": {
          "type": "accor_item",
          "settings": {
            "icon": "none",
            "title": "Are open-back headphones better for your ears?",
            "content": "<p>Open-back headphones are great for studio use, but open-ear headphones (or <strong>outside ear headphones</strong>) are better for ear health and safety in daily use. Open-ear headphones don't cover or block your ears, which reduces the risk of discomfort and ear fatigue during extended listening sessions.</p>"
          }
        },
        "accor_item_dnWyVp": {
          "type": "accor_item",
          "settings": {
            "icon": "none",
            "title": "Does open-back headphones cause ear pain?",
            "content": "<p>While open-back headphones are less likely to cause ear pain than in-ear earbuds, open-ear headphones, or <strong>out ear headphones</strong>, are the most comfortable option. They avoid placing any pressure on your ears, ensuring pain-free listening even during long periods of use.</p>"
          }
        },
